          content:
            "It was a Tuesday night. A developer merged a pull request at 11PM — small change, two lines of config. The pipeline picked it up automatically. Build passed. Tests passed. Docker image built. Deployed to production.\n\nAt 11:07PM the monitoring alert fired. Error rate 40%. The two-line config change had a typo in a database connection string. The app could not connect to the database. Every request was failing.\n\nHere is the painful part: the tests passed. Unit tests, integration tests — all green. Nobody had written a test that verified the database connection string format. The pipeline did exactly what it was configured to do. It deployed broken code, confidently and automatically, at 11PM.\n\nThe rollback took 4 minutes. The incident lasted 11 minutes. 11 minutes of 40% error rate on a Tuesday night — not catastrophic, but embarrassing. The post-mortem had one action item: add a smoke test after deployment that actually verifies the app can connect to the database before marking the deployment successful.\n\nThis is the lesson nobody teaches about CI/CD: a pipeline is only as good as its tests. Automation without verification is just faster failure delivery.",
