          content:
            "A startup's lead engineer opened his email on a Monday morning and saw an AWS bill notification. $47,000. For the weekend.\n\nWhat happened: a developer had written a script to process images. The script had a bug — an infinite loop that kept spawning new EC2 instances when processing failed instead of retrying on the same instance. It ran Friday night. By Sunday evening, 200 EC2 instances were running simultaneously, processing nothing, costing $8 per hour each.\n\nAWS did not stop it. AWS does not know your budget. AWS knows your credit card.\n\nThree things would have prevented this: a billing alert set at $500 (free, takes 2 minutes to configure), an IAM policy that limited how many EC2 instances the script's role could launch, and a CloudWatch alarm that alerted when EC2 instance count exceeded 10.\n\nNone of those existed. The company negotiated with AWS support and got a partial refund. The developer who wrote the script quit the week after.\n\nEvery DevOps engineer remembers the first time they saw an unexpected AWS bill. The ones who become senior engineers build guardrails before the bill arrives.",
