          content:
            "It was a Wednesday afternoon. A junior engineer was cleaning up a development environment. He ran terraform destroy in what he thought was the dev workspace. It was not the dev workspace.\n\nThe plan output showed 47 resources to be destroyed. EC2 instances, RDS databases, S3 buckets, VPCs. He typed yes.\n\nThe senior engineer across the room saw the Slack alert — RDS instance deletion initiated — and screamed. They ran to the terminal. Ctrl+C. Too late for 12 resources. The RDS instance deletion was already in progress.\n\nRDS has a deletion protection flag. It was not enabled. The database was gone in 4 minutes.\n\nThree hours later they had restored from the automated backup. The restore worked. No data was permanently lost. But 3 hours of data written after the last backup was gone forever.\n\nWhat should have existed: deletion_protection = true on every production RDS resource. A separate AWS account for production so dev tooling cannot touch it. Terraform workspaces with names that make the environment obvious. A CI/CD pipeline as the only way to apply Terraform in production — no human running terraform apply locally against prod.\n\nTerraform is powerful exactly because it can create and destroy real infrastructure with a single command. That power requires guardrails.",
