            "The disk that filled up at 3AM and took down the entire platform",
          content:
            "3:17AM. PagerDuty fires. The entire platform is down. No API is responding. You SSH into the application server.\n\ndf -h shows /var/log at 100%. The disk is completely full.\n\nWhat happened: a developer had added verbose debug logging two weeks ago to troubleshoot a production issue. He fixed the issue, forgot to turn off debug logging, and pushed to production. For two weeks, the application logged every single HTTP request in full detail — headers, body, response — to a log file with no rotation configured. 2TB of log files. The disk filled up at 3AM when traffic was lowest and nobody was watching.\n\nWhen the disk is full, Linux cannot write anything — no new files, no temp files, no socket files. The application cannot accept connections because it cannot write to its connection pool. Everything dies silently.\n\nFix: find /var/log -name '*.log' -size +1G to find the large files. truncate -s 0 application-debug.log to empty the file without deleting it while the application holds it open. Disk space recovered in 30 seconds. Platform back online.\n\nPermanent fix: logrotate configuration for all application logs, log level environment variable so debug logging can be turned off without a deployment, disk space CloudWatch alarm at 80% so you get the alert before the disk fills, not after.\n\nEvery Linux problem at 3AM is solvable if you know the right commands. This is why Linux fundamentals are non-negotiable for DevOps engineers.",
