          type: "concept",
          title:
            "The Linux knowledge that separates DevOps engineers who panic from those who fix things",
          content:
            "Linux is the operating system your code runs on in production. Every container, every EC2 instance, every Kubernetes pod runs on Linux. Understanding Linux at the right depth means the difference between a 3-minute fix and a 3-hour outage.\n\nFILE SYSTEM — know this completely:\n\n/etc — configuration files. /etc/nginx/nginx.conf, /etc/hosts, /etc/cron.d. The files that control how the system behaves.\n\n/var — variable data that changes at runtime. /var/log for logs, /var/run for PID files, /var/lib for application data. This is where disks fill up.\n\n/tmp — temporary files. Cleared on reboot. Applications use it for temp processing. On busy systems /tmp can fill up too.\n\n/proc — virtual filesystem exposing kernel and process information. /proc/cpuinfo shows CPU details. /proc/meminfo shows memory. /proc/PID/fd shows open file descriptors for a process. Not a real disk — it is the kernel exposing its state as files.\n\n/sys — another virtual filesystem for kernel and hardware information. Modern replacement for some /proc functionality.\n\nDISK MANAGEMENT COMMANDS:\n\ndf -h: Show disk usage for all mounted filesystems. -h for human-readable sizes. The first command to run when you suspect disk issues.\n\ndu -sh /var/log/*: Show size of each item in /var/log. Use to find what is consuming space.\n\nfind /var/log -name '*.log' -size +500M: Find log files larger than 500MB.\n\nlsof +D /var/log: Show all processes that have files open in /var/log. Critical when a disk is full — you cannot delete a file that a running process has open. The space is only reclaimed when the process closes the file or you truncate it.\n\ntruncate -s 0 /var/log/app.log: Empty a log file without deleting it. If a process has the file open, deleting it does not reclaim space — the inode stays allocated. Truncating empties it while keeping the file descriptor valid.\n\nPROCESS MANAGEMENT:\n\nps aux: Show all running processes with CPU and memory usage.\n\ntop / htop: Real-time process monitor. Shows CPU, memory, load average. htop has a better interface and allows killing processes directly.\n\nkill -9 PID: Send SIGKILL to a process — immediate termination, no cleanup. Use as last resort. kill PID sends SIGTERM first — graceful shutdown request.\n\nlsof -p PID: Show all files, sockets, and connections a process has open. Use to understand what a process is doing.\n\nstrace -p PID: Trace system calls made by a running process. Use to debug a stuck process — you can see exactly what it is waiting on.\n\njournalctl -u nginx --since '1 hour ago': View systemd service logs. -f to follow like tail -f.\n\nsystemctl status nginx: Check service status. systemctl restart nginx to restart. systemctl enable nginx to start on boot.\n\nNETWORKING COMMANDS:\n\nnetstat -tlnp / ss -tlnp: Show listening ports and which process is listening. -t TCP, -l listening, -n numeric ports, -p show process.\n\ncurl -v https://api.example.com/health: Test HTTP endpoint with verbose output showing headers, SSL handshake, response time.\n\ntcpdump -i eth0 port 80: Capture network traffic. Use to see exactly what packets are being sent and received. Powerful for debugging connection issues.\n\nping and traceroute: Basic connectivity and routing debug. traceroute shows each hop and latency — use to identify where in the network a connection is failing.\n\nnslookup / dig: DNS debugging. dig api.example.com shows the full DNS resolution chain. dig @8.8.8.8 api.example.com queries Google DNS specifically — use to check if DNS issue is in your resolver or upstream.\n\nSHELL SCRIPTING — the basics that make everything else possible:\n\nVariables:\nENV=production\necho $ENV\n\nLoops:\nfor server in web1 web2 web3; do\n  ssh $server 'sudo systemctl restart nginx'\ndone\n\nConditionals:\nif [ $EXIT_CODE -ne 0 ]; then\n  echo 'Deployment failed'\n  exit 1\nfi\n\nError handling — the most important shell scripting practice:\nset -euo pipefail\n\nset -e: Exit immediately if any command fails\nset -u: Treat unset variables as errors\nset -o pipefail: Pipeline fails if any command in it fails\n\nWithout these, a script can silently fail halfway through and leave infrastructure in a broken state. Always add set -euo pipefail at the top of every production script.\n\nUseful one-liners every DevOps engineer must know:\n\n# Find top 10 largest files on the system\nfind / -type f -exec du -sh {} + 2>/dev/null | sort -rh | head -10\n\n# Check which process is using port 8080\nlsof -i :8080\n\n# Count error lines in log file\ngrep -c 'ERROR' /var/log/app.log\n\n# Follow logs and filter for errors only\ntail -f /var/log/app.log | grep --line-buffered ERROR\n\n# Show memory usage sorted by process\nps aux --sort=-%mem | head -20\n\n# Check if a service is listening on expected port\nss -tlnp | grep :443\n\n# Archive and compress logs older than 7 days\nfind /var/log/app -name '*.log' -mtime +7 -exec gzip {} \\;\n\nLOG ANALYSIS:\n\ncat, head, tail: Basic file viewing. tail -f follows a file in real time.\n\ngrep: Search text. grep -r 'ERROR' /var/log searches recursively. grep -v excludes matches. grep -c counts matches.\n\nawk: Process structured text. awk '{print $1, $9}' /var/log/nginx/access.log prints IP and status code from nginx logs.\n\nsed: Stream editor. sed 's/old/new/g' for replacement. sed -n '100,200p' file prints lines 100-200.\n\ncut: Extract fields. cut -d',' -f2 extracts the second comma-separated field.\n\njq: JSON processing. curl api/health | jq '.status' extracts the status field from JSON response.\n\nPERMISSIONS:\n\nchmod 755 script.sh: Owner can read/write/execute. Group and others can read/execute.\nchown nginx:nginx /var/www/html: Change owner and group.\n\nThe production insight: never run application processes as root. Create a dedicated user with minimal permissions. If the application is compromised, the attacker has limited access.\n\nSUDO and privilege escalation:\n\nRun specific commands as root without a root shell: sudo systemctl restart nginx\n\nIn /etc/sudoers via visudo, grant specific commands without full root: deploy ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /bin/systemctl restart myapp\n\nThis is the principle of least privilege applied to Linux — the deploy user can restart the service but cannot do anything else as root.",
