            "Linux interview questions that reveal whether you have actually debugged production systems",
          content:
            "QUESTION 1: A server is running slowly. How do you diagnose it?\n\nWEAK (5/10): 'I would check the CPU and memory usage.'\n\nSTRONG (9/10): 'I start with the four key resources: CPU, memory, disk I/O, and network. top or htop shows CPU and memory in real time — I look for a process consuming unexpected CPU or memory. load average is important: if it exceeds the number of CPU cores consistently, the system is CPU-bound. For memory: free -h shows available memory and swap usage. If swap is being used heavily, the system is swapping to disk which causes severe slowness. For disk I/O: iostat -x 1 shows per-disk utilization and await time — high await means disk is the bottleneck. iotop shows which process is causing the disk I/O. For network: iftop or nethogs shows per-process network usage. After identifying the bottleneck I look at the specific process — lsof -p PID shows what files and connections it has open, strace -p PID shows what system calls it is making. The goal is to answer: is this a runaway process, a resource leak, or legitimate load that requires scaling?'\n\nSENIOR INSIGHT: Mentioning load average in relation to CPU core count is the detail that separates engineers who have read about Linux from those who have debugged production systems. A load average of 4.0 on a 4-core machine means the system is fully utilized. A load average of 4.0 on a 32-core machine means it is barely working. Context matters.\n\n---\n\nQUESTION 2: The disk is full. What do you do?\n\nWEAK (5/10): 'I would delete some log files to free up space.'\n\nSTRONG (9/10): 'First confirm with df -h which filesystem is full. Then find what is consuming space: du -sh /var/log/* sorted by size, and find / -size +1G -type f 2>/dev/null for large files anywhere on the system. Before deleting anything, check if any running process has the file open with lsof +D /directory — deleting a file that a process has open does not reclaim space until the process closes it. For log files specifically I use truncate -s 0 filename rather than rm — this empties the file while keeping it accessible to the process that has it open. For immediate relief I might also check /tmp and clear it if safe, and look for old Docker images and containers with docker system prune. Long term: set up logrotate for all application logs, add disk space monitoring that alerts at 80% not 100%, and review whether log verbosity is appropriate for production.'\n\nSENIOR INSIGHT: The lsof check before deleting, and truncate instead of rm for open files, is the operational knowledge that only comes from experience. Engineers who delete a log file and then wonder why disk space did not recover learn this lesson once and never forget it.\n\n---\n\nQUESTION 3: How do you find which process is listening on port 8080?\n\nWEAK (5/10): 'I would use netstat to check open ports.'\n\nSTRONG (9/10): 'I use ss -tlnp | grep :8080 — ss is the modern replacement for netstat, faster and more accurate. The flags: -t for TCP, -l for listening only, -n for numeric ports, -p to show the process. This shows the PID and process name. Alternatively lsof -i :8080 shows the same information with more detail including the user running the process. If I need to identify what the process is doing, I then run ps -p PID -f for the full command line and lsof -p PID to see all files and connections it has open. In a container environment I would also check docker ps and kubectl get pods to identify which container is using the port.'\n\nSENIOR INSIGHT: Knowing that ss has replaced netstat and using it fluently signals that you are current with Linux tooling. Also mentioning the container context shows you think in modern infrastructure terms, not just bare-metal Linux.\n\n---\n\nQUESTION 4: Explain what happens when you run a command in the shell.\n\nWEAK (5/10): 'The shell executes the command and shows the output.'\n\nSTRONG (9/10): 'The shell parses the command, splitting it into tokens. It checks if it is a shell builtin like cd or export — if so, executes it directly. For external commands, it searches PATH directories for an executable with that name. Once found, the shell calls fork() to create a child process — an exact copy of the shell process. The child calls execve() to replace itself with the command executable. The parent shell calls waitpid() and blocks until the child exits. The child process inherits the parent shell environment including stdin, stdout, stderr, and environment variables. The exit code of the command is stored in $? and is 0 for success, non-zero for failure. This fork-exec model is why your shell environment changes in a script do not affect the parent shell — they happen in a child process.'\n\nSENIOR INSIGHT: Explaining fork() and exec() at the system call level signals deep Linux knowledge. The observation that environment changes in a script do not persist to the parent shell — and why — is the kind of insight that explains a confusing behavior many engineers have encountered without understanding.\n\n---\n\nQUESTION 5: What is the difference between a hard link and a soft link?\n\nWEAK (5/10): 'A soft link is like a shortcut and a hard link is a direct reference to the file.'\n\nSTRONG (9/10): 'A hard link is a directory entry that points directly to an inode — the data structure that stores file metadata and the actual data blocks. Multiple hard links to the same inode mean multiple names for the same file. Deleting one hard link does not delete the data — the data is only deleted when the inode reference count reaches zero, meaning all hard links are deleted. Hard links cannot cross filesystem boundaries and cannot link to directories. A soft link or symlink is a special file that contains a path string pointing to another file or directory. It can cross filesystems and can link to directories. If the target is deleted, the symlink becomes a dangling symlink pointing to nothing. In practice: use symlinks for most use cases. Hard links are useful in backup tools where you want multiple directory trees to share the same data blocks without duplication.\n\nSENIOR INSIGHT: Explaining inodes and reference counts shows you understand the Linux filesystem at the level that helps you debug real problems — like why deleting a file does not free disk space when another hard link exists, or why a deleted file still consumes space when a process has it open.\n\nFOLLOW-UP PROBES:\n- What is the difference between a process and a thread in Linux?\n- How does the Linux OOM killer decide which process to kill?\n- What is cgroups and how does Docker use it?\n- How do you schedule a recurring task in Linux?\n- What is the difference between /dev/null and /dev/zero?\n- How do you check which system calls a process is making?\n- What is a zombie process and how do you deal with it?",
