          title: "The force push that rewrote history and broke the entire team",
          content:
            "It was a Monday morning. A senior developer was cleaning up his feature branch before merging. He had made some messy commits over the weekend and wanted a clean history. He ran git rebase -i to squash them, then pushed.\n\nGit rejected it. 'Updates were rejected because the tip of your current branch is behind its remote counterpart.'\n\nHe did not read the message carefully. He ran git push --force.\n\nAt that moment, three other developers had already pulled his branch to review his code. Their local copies now had commits that no longer existed on the remote. Every subsequent git pull for those three developers failed with conflicts they did not understand. One developer, panicking, ran git push --force on the main branch trying to fix it.\n\nNow main branch history was rewritten. The CI/CD pipeline was running against commits that did not exist anymore. Two deployments were in flight against orphaned commits.\n\nIt took a senior engineer 45 minutes to reconstruct the correct history using git reflog — the one command that saves you when everything else is broken.\n\nThe rule that prevents this: never force push to a shared branch. Never. On your own feature branch before anyone else has pulled it — fine. On main, develop, or any branch others are working from — never. Use git push --force-with-lease instead, which fails if someone else has pushed since you last pulled.",
